column76: Palm Beach County, Florida, United States
column153: I saw it while driving on 441N somewhere between Floral Acres and Boynton Beach Boulevard on the Northeast side of 441. It was in a very rural undeveloped area. It was in the grass on the side of the road. It was a very large dark colored lizard with a flicking tongue. At first I thought it was a very large iguana, but as I passed it I noticed it was not moving like an iguana. It was very fast and it had the flicking tongue that very big lizards have. It may have been a Nile Monitor, or another type of Monitor Lizard because of its shape. It was somewhere between 3-5 feet in length, but hard to determine driving at 45-50 mph. It was sighted about 9 AM this morning, and I would have reported it sooner had I known there was an actual site to report it on. I was googling photos of lizards to try and Identify it when I came across this reporting site.

column69: The Lizard was sitting on the rocks outside of the golf shop just to the left of the stairs.  It appeared that the lizard was living underneath the golf shop .
column153: I saw what I was told was a Nile Monitor Lizard.  It had a flat head, large snout, long claws and a long mouth.  It was about 4 feet long.  It was sitting on some rocks next to the Golf Shop at the Cooper Colony Golf Course in Cooper City Florida, Broward County.

column153: Relaxing on Chamberlain and Bluebird in North Port,FL in broad daylight. Did not look happy when we interruppted him. Looked at us and ran quite quickly into the woods. Monitor identified from photograph at University of Florida IFAS Extention (http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/). Highly probably it is a Nile monitor, but the species cannot be determined from the photographs (Dr. Kenney Krysko, Univesity of Floirda, and Dr. Todd Campbell, University of Tampa, personal communication). Vouchered at FLMNH as Varanus sp.

column69: Cape Coral, SW 15th Pl appx 200 m N  of SW 10th St
column153: A monitor lizard walking on top of the metal beams on my pool cage. It walked all along the cage to the edge of back of cage. I tryed spraying it with water to get it to jump off onto the grass, but it just turned around and scurried back across top of pool cage and went on my tile roof. When I first moved here in April 2006 I had the state wildlife expert here trapping a 6 foot female across the street. I also had a nest of babies hatch behind my pool cage on the grass next to pool wall. Traps were left for a week to try to catch babies. This monitor was 1 foot long from head to tail. I have no camera to take photo.

column27: Michael Renda, The Nature Conservancy, personal communication
column69: West Palm Beach, west end of 45th St
column76: Palm Beach County, Florida, United States
column153: Two observations during the early fall of 2008, both at the very westward end of 45th St. in West Palm Beach. At the time this location was fenced off and not available to the public, but since then has been turned into a parking lot for the new trail system that SWA has put in. Both individuals noted that the monitor had a distinctive walk and a forked tongue, and was not a gator or Iguana. At that time, extensive effort was put in locating the existence of a monitor by a biologist with FDA APHIS Wildlife Services, without success. This area has a very large gator population, as well as a lot of people using the trails, so if there was a monitor it has been eaten or has moved on by now. There have been no other know observations of another monitor since this time (from Mark McLean, SWA) Site was was fenced off and not available to the public, but has been turned into a parking lot for the new trail system that Solid Waste Authority has put in.
